data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Timeout Enforcement Pattern

### What breaks in .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered — dead code |

### Why it broke

.NET 6+ removed preemptive thread abortion entirely. You **cannot** forcibly kill a managed thread. The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until the task completes or the timeout fires.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The code above detaches from waiting, but the delegate keeps running on the thread pool. If `work` must **cooperate** with cancellation (stop doing real work), change the signature:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work checks the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **Fire-and-forget delegate** | Without the `CancellationToken` overload, `work` keeps running after timeout — it just isn't waited on. This leaks CPU/resources. Prefer the token-accepting signature. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timer is `IDisposable`. Always wrap in `using` or the internal timer leaks. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from unrelated cancellations. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` checkpoints. Long gaps between checks = delayed cancellation. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls code you can't modify and it never checks a token, it **will not stop**. The only way to truly kill uncooperative code is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()`. |

### Async version (preferred if callers can be async)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

This is the cleanest path — fully async, no thread pool blocking, and `WaitAsync` (available since .NET 6) handles the timeout detach.
